# Financial Amount Safety

## Always floor, never round

Display amounts must be **<=** on-chain amounts. `Math.round` can round UP, causing "Insufficient balance" when user clicks "All".

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — rounds 1.1286 to 1.13, user tries to spend 1.13 but only has 1.1286
const sui = Math.round(raw / 1e9 * 100) / 100;

// ✅ GOOD — floors to 1.12, always safe
const sui = Math.floor(raw / 1e9 * 10000) / 10000;
```

For ALL assets in `useBalance.ts`, floor to the token's on-chain decimal precision (capped at 8dp).

## Dynamic precision for small amounts

Preset calculations must scale with amount magnitude. `Math.floor(0.000434 * 0.25 * 100) / 100` = 0 (useless).

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — hardcoded 2dp, zeros out tiny amounts
const q25 = Math.floor(held * 0.25 * 100) / 100;

// ✅ GOOD — dynamic precision based on magnitude
const dp = held >= 1 ? 100 : held >= 0.01 ? 10000 : 100000000;
const q25 = Math.floor(held * 0.25 * dp) / dp;
```

## Unified balance lookups — no per-asset special casing

Use `heldAmount(symbol)` and `heldUsd(symbol)` from `page.tsx`. Never duplicate `if SUI... else if USDC... else...` logic across multiple functions.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — duplicated in 4 places, each slightly different
if (sym === 'USDC') held = balance.usdc;
else if (sym === 'SUI') held = balance.sui;
else held = balance.assetBalances[from];

// ✅ GOOD — single utility, used everywhere
const held = heldAmount(symbol);
```

When adding new swap/balance features, use `heldAmount()` and `heldUsd()` — never add per-asset branches.
